\begin_layout Title
General Equilibrium Analysis of a Two-Good CES Economy 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash

\backslash
 
\end_layout

\end_inset

with Labor Input and Task-based Production
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Note Note
status open

\begin_layout Section*
Economic Setup
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
First,
 we present a General Equilibrium (GE) model that abstracts from the specifics of how tasks are performed in the production process.
 Later,
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand vpageref
reference "sec:task_based_production"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

,
 we will extend the framework to incorporate task-based production.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
Consumer Preferences
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
The representative consumer has a CES utility function over two goods,
 given by:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
U(x_{1},x_{2})=\left[\delta x_{1}^{\rho}+(1-\delta)x_{2}^{\rho}\right]^{\frac{1}{\rho}},\quad0<\delta<1,\quad\rho<1.
\]

\end_inset

The elasticity of substitution is defined as:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\sigma=\frac{1}{1-\rho}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
Production
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
A single firm produces two goods using labor as the only input.
 Good 1 requires 
\begin_inset Formula $l_{1}$
\end_inset

 units of labor per unit of output while good 2 requires 
\begin_inset Formula $l_{2}$
\end_inset

 units of labor per unit of output.
 Under perfect competition,
 the price of each good equals its marginal cost:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
p_{1}=wl_{1},\quad p_{2}=wl_{2}.
\]

\end_inset

Setting 
\begin_inset Formula $w=1$
\end_inset

 as a numeraire simplifies prices to:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
p_{1}=l_{1},\quad p_{2}=l_{2}.\label{eq:firm_price}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
Labor Market Constraints
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
The consumer has one unit of labor that is supplied inelastically.
 Thus,
 the total labor constraint is:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
l_{1}x_{1}+l_{2}x_{2}=1,\label{eq:labor_market}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where the left hand side is the labor demanded by the firm for producing good 1 and good 2.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section*
Solving for General Equilibrium
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
Consumer Optimization
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
The consumer maximizes utility subject to the budget constraint:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
p_{1}x_{1}+p_{2}x_{2}=1.
\]

\end_inset

The marginal rate of substitution (MRS) is equated to the price ratio:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{\partial U/\partial x_{1}}{\partial U/\partial x_{2}}=\frac{p_{1}}{p_{2}}.
\]

\end_inset

From the CES utility function and 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:firm_price"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{\delta x_{1}^{\rho-1}}{(1-\delta)x_{2}^{\rho-1}}=\frac{l_{1}}{l_{2}}.
\]

\end_inset

Rearranging:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left(\frac{x_{1}}{x_{2}}\right)^{\rho-1}=\frac{l_{1}}{l_{2}}\cdot\frac{1-\delta}{\delta}.
\]

\end_inset

Define:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
R=\left(\frac{l_{1}}{l_{2}}\cdot\frac{1-\delta}{\delta}\right)^{-\sigma}.
\]

\end_inset

Thus,
 the ratio of equilibrium consumption is:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\frac{x_{1}}{x_{2}}=R.\label{eq:consumption_ratio}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
Solving for 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{2}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Substituting for 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{1}$
\end_inset

 from 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:consumption_ratio"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 into the labor constraint 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:labor_market"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 gives:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
l_{1}Rx_{2}+l_{2}x_{2}=1.
\]

\end_inset

Solving for 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{2}$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
x_{2}^{*}=\frac{1}{l_{1}R+l_{2}}.
\]

\end_inset

Thus,
 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{1}^{*}$
\end_inset

 is:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
x_{1}^{*}=Rx_{2}^{*}=\frac{R}{l_{1}R+l_{2}}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section*
Sectoral Employment
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
Employment in Each Sector
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
The labor employed in each sector is:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
L_{1}^{*}=l_{1}x_{1}^{*}=\frac{l_{1}R}{l_{1}R+l_{2}},
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
L_{2}^{*}=l_{2}x_{2}^{*}=\frac{l_{2}}{l_{1}R+l_{2}}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
General Equilibrium Summary
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
The following characterize the equilibrium prices and allocations:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
w & =1,\\
p_{1} & =l_{1},\\
p_{2} & =l_{2},\\
x_{1} & =\frac{R}{l_{1}R+l_{2}},\\
x_{2} & =\frac{l_{2}}{l_{1}R+l_{2}}\\
L_{1} & =\frac{l_{1}R}{l_{1}R+l_{2}},\\
L_{2} & =\frac{l_{2}}{l_{1}R+l_{2}},
\end{align*}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $R=\left(\frac{l_{1}}{l_{2}}\cdot\frac{1-\delta}{\delta}\right)^{-\sigma}$
\end_inset

 is the relative consumption of good 1 to good 2,
 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{x_{1}}{x_{2}}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section*
Comparative Statics with Respect to Automation of a Task in Production of 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{1}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
This section examines how equilibrium allocations and prices adjust in response to changes in input requirements,
 with a particular focus on variations in 
\begin_inset Formula $l_{1}$
\end_inset

,
 the labor input necessary for producing good 1.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
Price Effects
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
A decrease in 
\begin_inset Formula $l_{1}$
\end_inset

 reduces the price of good 1 relative to both wages and good 2:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{\partial p_{1}}{\partial l_{1}}=\frac{\partial}{\partial l_{1}}\left(l_{1}\right)=1>0.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
Effect on Consumption Ratios (
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
To understand how equilibrium consumption changes,
 we first analyze the sensitivity of 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 with respect to 
\begin_inset Formula $l_{1}$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\frac{\partial R}{\partial l_{1}} & =\frac{\partial}{\partial l_{1}}\left(\left(\frac{l_{1}}{l_{2}}\cdot\frac{1-\delta}{\delta}\right)^{-\sigma}\right)\\
 & =\frac{\partial}{\partial l_{1}}\left(l_{1}^{-\sigma}\left(\frac{1}{l_{2}}\cdot\frac{1-\delta}{\delta}\right)^{-\sigma}\right)\\
 & =\frac{l_{1}^{-\sigma-1}}{-\sigma}\left(\frac{1}{l_{2}}\cdot\frac{1-\delta}{\delta}\right)^{-\sigma}\\
 & =-\frac{1}{\sigma}.\frac{1}{l_{1}}\left(\frac{l_{1}}{l_{2}}\cdot\frac{1-\delta}{\delta}\right)^{-\sigma}
\end{align*}

\end_inset

Simplifying:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{\partial R}{\partial l_{1}}=-\frac{1}{\sigma}\cdot\frac{R}{l_{1}}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
Change in Consumption of Good 2 (
\begin_inset Formula $x_{2}^{*}$
\end_inset

):
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
The effect of a change in 
\begin_inset Formula $l_{1}$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{2}^{*}$
\end_inset

 is:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\frac{\partial x_{2}^{*}}{\partial l_{1}} & =\frac{\partial}{\partial l_{1}}\left(\frac{1}{l_{1}R+l_{2}}\right)\\
 & =-\frac{\frac{\partial}{\partial l_{1}}\left(l_{1}R+l_{2}\right)}{\left(l_{1}R+l_{2}\right)^{2}}\\
 & =-\frac{R+l_{1}\frac{\partial R}{\partial l_{1}}}{\left(l_{1}R+l_{2}\right)^{2}}\\
 & =-R\frac{1-\frac{1}{\sigma}}{\left(l_{1}R+l_{2}\right)^{2}}\\
 & =-\left(\frac{\sigma-1}{\sigma}\right)\frac{R}{\left(l_{1}R+l_{2}\right)^{2}}.
\end{align*}

\end_inset

The sign of 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{\partial x_{2}^{*}}{\partial l_{1}}$
\end_inset

 depends on 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\sigma>1\ (\text{substitutes}) & \Leftrightarrow\frac{\partial x_{2}^{*}}{\partial l_{1}}<0\Leftrightarrow x_{2}^{*}\uparrow\ \text{when}\ l_{1}\downarrow,\\
\sigma<1\ (\text{complements}) & \Leftrightarrow\frac{\partial x_{2}^{*}}{\partial l_{1}}>0\Leftrightarrow x_{2}^{*}\downarrow\ \text{when}\ l_{1}\downarrow,\\
\sigma=1\ (\text{Cobb-Douglas}) & \Leftrightarrow\frac{\partial x_{2}^{*}}{\partial l_{1}}=0\Leftrightarrow x_{2}^{*}\ \text{unchanged}.
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
Change in Consumption of Good 1 (
\begin_inset Formula $x_{1}^{*}$
\end_inset

)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
The effect of a change in 
\begin_inset Formula $l_{1}$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{1}^{*}$
\end_inset

 is:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\frac{\partial x_{1}^{*}}{\partial l_{1}} & =\frac{\partial}{\partial l_{1}}\left(\frac{R}{l_{1}R+l_{2}}\right)\\
 & =\frac{\frac{\partial R}{\partial l_{1}}.\left(l_{1}R+l_{2}\right)-R.\frac{\partial}{\partial l_{1}}\left(l_{1}R+l_{2}\right)}{\left(l_{1}R+l_{2}\right)^{2}}\\
 & =\frac{\frac{\partial R}{\partial l_{1}}.\left(l_{1}R+l_{2}\right)-R\left(R+l_{1}\frac{\partial R}{\partial l_{1}}\right)}{\left(l_{1}R+l_{2}\right)^{2}}\\
 & =\frac{\frac{\partial R}{\partial l_{1}}.\left(l_{1}R+l_{2}-Rl_{1}\right)-R^{2}}{\left(l_{1}R+l_{2}\right)^{2}}\\
 & =\frac{-\frac{1}{\sigma}.\frac{R}{l_{1}}.l_{2}-R^{2}}{\left(l_{1}R+l_{2}\right)^{2}}\\
 & =-\frac{R}{\left(l_{1}R+l_{2}\right)^{2}}\left(\frac{1}{\sigma}\frac{l_{2}}{l_{1}}+R\right).
\end{align*}

\end_inset

This means that consumption of good 1 always decreases.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
Effect on Labor Share of Goods
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
We have:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\frac{\partial L_{2}^{*}}{\partial l_{1}} & =\frac{\partial}{\partial l_{1}}\left(l_{2}x_{2}\right)\\
 & =l_{2}\frac{\partial}{\partial l_{1}}\left(x_{2}\right)\\
 & =-\left(\frac{\sigma-1}{\sigma}\right)\frac{l_{2}R}{\left(l_{1}R+l_{2}\right)^{2}}.
\end{align*}

\end_inset

That is,
 the direction of changes in labor share of good 2 is similar to changes in consumption of good 2.
 The labor share of good 1 moves in the opposite direction of consumption and labor share of good 2 because labor is supplied inelastically.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*
Comparative Statics Summary
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
In short:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\frac{\partial p_{1}^{*}}{\partial l_{1}} & =1,\\
\frac{\partial p_{2}^{*}}{\partial l_{1}} & =0,\\
\frac{\partial R}{\partial l_{1}} & =-\frac{1}{\sigma}\cdot\frac{R}{l_{1}},\\
\frac{\partial x_{1}^{*}}{\partial l_{1}} & =-\frac{R}{\left(l_{1}R+l_{2}\right)^{2}}\left(\frac{1}{\sigma}\frac{l_{2}}{l_{1}}+R\right),\\
\frac{\partial x_{2}^{*}}{\partial l_{1}} & =-\left(\frac{\sigma-1}{\sigma}\right)\frac{R}{\left(l_{1}R+l_{2}\right)^{2}},\\
\frac{\partial L_{2}^{*}}{\partial l_{1}} & =-\left(\frac{\sigma-1}{\sigma}\right)\frac{l_{2}R}{\left(l_{1}R+l_{2}\right)^{2}},\\
\frac{dL_{1}^{*}}{dl_{1}} & =-\left(\frac{\partial L_{2}^{*}}{\partial l_{1}}\right).
\end{align*}

\end_inset


