\begin_layout Section*
Task-Based Production
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sec:task_based_production"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Now,
 imagine production of good 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 requires completing a set of specific tasks denoted by 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{T}_{k}$
\end_inset

.
 A worker employed in task 
\begin_inset Formula $i\in\mathcal{T}_{k}$
\end_inset

 must acquire human capital 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{i}^{k}>0$
\end_inset

 to perform the task.
 We assume that tasks within 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{T}_{k}$
\end_inset

 require fixed proportions of labor per unit of output,
 meaning the firm does not allocate labor freely across tasks but instead determines the total amount of labor,
 
\begin_inset Formula $l_{k}$
\end_inset

,
 required to produce one unit of good 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
This assumption captures the idea that tasks must be performed in pre-determined ratios.
 For example,
 suppose task 
\begin_inset Formula $i\in\mathcal{T}_{k}$
\end_inset

 takes 30 minutes to complete,
 while task 
\begin_inset Formula $j\in\mathcal{T}_{k}$
\end_inset

 (where 
\begin_inset Formula $j\neq i$
\end_inset

) takes 45 minutes.
 Since these tasks must be completed together to produce a unit of good 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

,
 the firm must allocate a total of 75 minutes of labor per unit.
 It is not possible to perform task 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 twice while completing task 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

 only once—
both tasks must be executed in a fixed proportion.
 Therefore,
 rather than specifying labor requirements separately for each task,
 we express production using a single labor input,
 
\begin_inset Formula $l_{k}$
\end_inset

,
 which aggregates the total labor required across all tasks.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
In a competitive final goods market,
 firms fully compensate (representative) workers for the human capital they have acquired for their respective tasks in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{T}_{k}$
\end_inset

.
 Suppose there are two goods,
 each produced using distinct task sets 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{T}_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{T}_{2}$
\end_inset

.
 The resulting prices of goods are:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
p_{1} & =(1+\sum_{i\in\mathcal{T}_{1}}c_{i}^{1}),\\
p_{2} & =(1+\sum_{i\in\mathcal{T}_{2}}c_{i}^{2}).
\end{align*}

\end_inset

As before,
 free entry ensures that:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
p_{1} & =(1+\sum_{i\in\mathcal{T}_{1}}c_{i}^{1})=l_{1},\\
p_{2} & =(1+\sum_{i\in\mathcal{T}_{2}}c_{i}^{2})=l_{2}.
\end{align*}

\end_inset

We can now express equilibrium allocations and labor shares as functions of the human capital required to produce each good.
 The equilibrium conditions are:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
w & =1,\\
p_{1} & =(1+\sum_{i\in\mathcal{T}_{1}}c_{i}^{1}),\\
p_{2} & =(1+\sum_{i\in\mathcal{T}_{2}}c_{i}^{2}),\\
x_{1} & =\frac{R}{(1+\sum_{i\in\mathcal{T}_{1}}c_{i}^{1})R+(1+\sum_{i\in\mathcal{T}_{2}}c_{i}^{2})},\\
x_{2} & =\frac{l_{2}}{(1+\sum_{i\in\mathcal{T}_{1}}c_{i}^{1})R+(1+\sum_{i\in\mathcal{T}_{2}}c_{i}^{2})}\\
L_{1} & =\frac{(1+\sum_{i\in\mathcal{T}_{1}}c_{i}^{1})R}{(1+\sum_{i\in\mathcal{T}_{1}}c_{i}^{1})R+(1+\sum_{i\in\mathcal{T}_{2}}c_{i}^{2})},\\
L_{2} & =\frac{l_{2}}{(1+\sum_{i\in\mathcal{T}_{1}}c_{i}^{1})R+(1+\sum_{i\in\mathcal{T}_{2}}c_{i}^{2})},
\end{align*}

\end_inset

with 
\begin_inset Formula $R=\left(\frac{(1+\sum_{i\in\mathcal{T}_{1}}c_{i}^{1})}{(1+\sum_{i\in\mathcal{T}_{2}}c_{i}^{2})}\cdot\frac{1-\delta}{\delta}\right)^{\frac{1}{1-\sigma}}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section*
General Equilibrium Effects of Task Automation
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Using this task-based framework,
 automation can be interpreted as the removal of a subset of tasks,
 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{A}_{k}\subseteq\mathcal{T}_{k}$
\end_inset

,
 from the production process,
 possibly at some automation cost 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{C}_{k}$
\end_inset

.
 Once tasks in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{A}_{k}$
\end_inset

 no longer require human labor,
 the total human capital needed to produce good 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 decreases.
 This implies that automation lowers the price of the automated good.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
To analyze the post-automation equilibrium in the two-good economy,
 we refer to the comparative statics derived earlier.
 Suppose some tasks 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{A}_{1}\subseteq\mathcal{T}_{1}$
\end_inset

 (
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{A}_{1}\neq\emptyset$
\end_inset

) in production of good 1 are automated.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{\mathcal{T}_{1}}\equiv\mathcal{T}_{1}\backslash\mathcal{A}_{1}$
\end_inset

 the set of tasks still performed by human labor after automation.
 Since some tasks are removed,
 
\begin_inset Formula $|\tilde{\mathcal{T}_{1}}|<|\mathcal{T}_{1}|$
\end_inset

.
 Thus,
 the new price of good 1 is:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\tilde{p}_{1}=(1+\sum_{i\in\tilde{\mathcal{T}}_{1}}c_{i}^{1})<(1+\sum_{i\in\mathcal{T}_{1}}c_{i}^{1})=p_{1}
\]

\end_inset

Since price of good 1 decreases,
 the total labor require for good 1,
 
\begin_inset Formula $l_{1}$
\end_inset

,
 also decreases in the new equilibrium.
 The comparative statics for a decrease in 
\begin_inset Formula $l_{1}$
\end_inset

 are characterized by the following set of equations:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\frac{\partial p_{1}^{*}}{\partial l_{1}} & =1,\\
\frac{\partial p_{2}^{*}}{\partial l_{1}} & =0,\\
\frac{\partial R}{\partial l_{1}} & =-\frac{1}{\sigma}\cdot\frac{R}{l_{1}},\\
\frac{\partial x_{1}^{*}}{\partial l_{1}} & =-\frac{R}{\left(l_{1}R+l_{2}\right)^{2}}\left(\frac{1}{\sigma}\frac{l_{2}}{l_{1}}+R\right),\\
\frac{\partial x_{2}^{*}}{\partial l_{1}} & =-\left(\frac{\sigma-1}{\sigma}\right)\frac{R}{\left(l_{1}R+l_{2}\right)^{2}},\\
\frac{\partial L_{2}^{*}}{\partial l_{1}} & =-\left(\frac{\sigma-1}{\sigma}\right)\frac{l_{2}R}{\left(l_{1}R+l_{2}\right)^{2}},\\
\frac{dL_{1}^{*}}{dl_{1}} & =-\left(\frac{\partial L_{2}^{*}}{\partial l_{1}}\right).
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

